-- t14. The Greek Bible and Jewish Concepts of Royal Priesthood and Priestly Monarchy -- t15. Royal Ideology: 1 and 2 Maccabees and Egypt -- t16. Constructing Kings—from the Ptolemies to the Herodians: The Archaeological Evidence -- tCumulative Bibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndexes General -- tAncient Sources -- tModern Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume gathers sixteen essays on monarchy and power in the Hellenistic period and charts a new approach to Hellenistic history by focusing attention on biblical and Jewish evidence and reading that evidence in new ways. The essays consider the kings, queens, and power figures of the Hellenistic dynasties, as well as ancient Israelite kings, the Babylonian and Persian rulers of the Bible, Parthians, and Romans. The volume also represents a new kind of interpretation of the Greek Bible (Septuagint) and of the Jewish literature of the period, setting them in the context of Hellenistic political thought and practice.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAitken, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAitken, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlexander, Loveday, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDines, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDines, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdwards, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https:/